\begin_layout Title
Notes on Green's functions in inhomogeneous media
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
S.
 G.
 Johnson, MIT Course 18.303
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Homogeneous media
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have Poisson's equation with constant coefficients (
\begin_inset Formula $=1$
\end_inset

 for simplicity), i.e.
 in a homogeneous medium, i.e.
 in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

empty space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
-\nabla^{2}u=f\]

\end_inset

in some region 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, with boundary conditions so that this has a unique solution, e.g.
 Dirichlet boundaries 
\begin_inset Formula $u|_{d\Omega}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can write the solution in terms of the Green's function 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
u(\vec{x})=\int_{\Omega}G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')f(\vec{x}')d^{n}\vec{x}',\label{eq:G0}\end{equation}

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 dimensions, where 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla^{2}G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')=\delta(\vec{x}-\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')=\frac{1}{4\pi|\vec{x}-\vec{x}'|}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Inhomogeneous media
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, suppose we have non-constant coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\vec{x})>0$
\end_inset

, corresponding to an inhomogeneous medium (i.e.
 different 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

materials
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at different points in space).
 This could enter Poisson's equation in several ways, for example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $-c\nabla^{2}u=f$
\end_inset

 --- for example, in a stretched string or drum, 
\begin_inset Formula $1/c$
\end_inset

 would be proportional to the density, so 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 would represent a variable density.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla\cdot(c\nabla u)=f$
\end_inset

 --- for example, in electrostatics 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{c}$
\end_inset

 would be proportional to the refractive index; in a stretched string or
 drum 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 would be proportional to a tension/elasticity; in a diffusion problem 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 would be a diffusion coefficient; in a heat-conduction problem 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 would be proportional to a thermal conductivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla^{2}u+cu=f$
\end_inset

 --- for example, in quantum mechanics this would represent SchrÃ¶dinger's
 equation with a variable potential energy 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Various other generalizations and combinations.
 e.g.
 a multidimensional Sturm--Liouville equation, 
\begin_inset Formula $-c_{1}\nabla\cdot(c_{2}\nabla u)+c_{3}u=f$
\end_inset

, for different functions 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1,2,3}(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}$
\end_inset

 could even be a positive-definite matrix).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All of these are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}u=f$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 is self-adjoint and positive-definite (assuming zero Dirichlet boundary
 conditions and an appropriate inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,v\rangle$
\end_inset

), as we've seen previously in class, so they should have unique solutions
 (excluding pathological 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 functions).
 However, the solutions may in general be quite different from those of
 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla^{2}u=f$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
Can we relate them to 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}$
\end_inset

, the Green's function for empty space?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $-c\nabla^{2}u=f$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This case is quite trivial to relate to empty space: just rewrite it as
 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla^{2}u=f/c$
\end_inset

 (valid since 
\begin_inset Formula $c>0$
\end_inset

), in which case we can use eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:G0"

\end_inset

) to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula \[
u(\vec{x})=\int_{\Omega}G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')\frac{f(\vec{x}')}{c(\vec{x}')}d^{n}\vec{x}',\]

\end_inset

from which it follows that the Green's function of this problem is 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\vec{x},\vec{x}')=G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')/c(\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla\cdot(c\nabla u)=f$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make it look like empty space, we employ the product rule to write 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla(c\nabla u)=(\nabla c)\cdot(\nabla u)+c\nabla^{2}u$
\end_inset

, obtaining: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
-\nabla^{2}u=\frac{f}{c}+\frac{\nabla c}{c}\cdot\nabla u.\]

\end_inset

If we substitute the right-hand side as if it were 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the empty-space problem, from eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:G0"

\end_inset

), and note that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\nabla c)/c=\nabla\ln c$
\end_inset

, we obtain: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
u(\vec{x})=\int_{\Omega}G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')\left[\frac{f(\vec{x}')}{c(\vec{x}')}+\nabla'[\ln c(\vec{x}')]\cdot\nabla'u(\vec{x}')\right]d^{n}\vec{x}'.\label{eq:VIE}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Notice, however, that the unknown 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 appears on both the left- and right-hand sides.
 This is a 
\series bold
volume integral equation
\series default

\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
More specifically, it is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

second-kind
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 integral equation, since 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 appears both inside and outside the integral.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

.
 There are various numerical methods to solve such 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

VIE
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problems approximately by discretizing space, but we won't cover these
 in 18.303.
 However, there are still several lessons to be learned from this equation.
 First, one can think of the inhomogeneous solution as the sum of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

homogeneous
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

 from the right-hand-sides 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\vec{x}')/c$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}'$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
plus a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

scattered
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 solution
\series default
 from the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 creating 
\series bold
new source terms at inhomogeneities
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla c$
\end_inset

.
 Second, there are various general situations where this VIE simplifies
 considerably.
 In the following, denote 
\begin_inset Formula \[
u_{0}(\vec{x})=\int_{\Omega}G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')\frac{f(\vec{x}')}{c(\vec{x}')}d^{n}\vec{x}',\]

\end_inset

the part of 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 that 
\emph on
doesn't
\emph default
 come from the inhomogeneity 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla c$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

incident
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 solution.
 We then can write 
\begin_inset Formula $u=u_{0}+\hat{B}u$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 is the linear 
\emph on
integral
\emph default
 operator corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}u=\int G_{0}\nabla'\ln c\cdot\nabla'u$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(This terminology of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

incident
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

scattered
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 parts of the solution has its origins in wave-equation problems, where
 the solution represents a wave propagating outwards from a source 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, and is actually bouncing off of objects/inhomogeneities.
 In the present problem, there is no time dependence so this terminology
 is only an analogy.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Piecewise-homogeneous media
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most common and important case of inhomogeneous media is where 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
piecewise-constant
\series default
.
 e.g.
 in one region you have glass, in another region you have metal, and in
 another region you have water, each corresponding to a different constant
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, suppose we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla\cdot(c\nabla u)=f$
\end_inset

 for the situation depicted in figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:piecewise-inhomog"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\vec{x})=c_{1}$
\end_inset

 in some volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $=c_{2}$
\end_inset

 outside of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

