	filename piecewise-inhomog.eps
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:piecewise-inhomog"

\end_inset

Schematic example of piecewise-constant coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\vec{x})=c_{1}$
\end_inset

 in some region 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 (with boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $dV$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\vec{n}}$
\end_inset

 denoting the outward unit-normal vector), and 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\vec{x})=c_{2}$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 In this case 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\ln c$
\end_inset

 is actually a delta function at the interface, multiplied by the magnitude
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln c_{2}-\ln c_{1}=\ln(c_{2}/c_{1})$
\end_inset

 of the discontinuity, also multiplied by a unit-normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\vec{n}}$
\end_inset

 at each point on the interface (giving the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\ln c$
\end_inset

).
 Then the VIE
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VIE"

\end_inset

) simplifies to 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 plus a 
\emph on
surface integral
\emph default
: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
u(\vec{x})=u_{0}(\vec{x})+\ln(c_{2}/c_{1})\oiint_{dV}G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')\nabla'u(\vec{x}')\cdot d\vec{A}',\label{eq:SIE}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d\vec{A}'=\hat{\vec{n}}dA'$
\end_inset

 is the usual outward-normal differential area in a surface integral.
 This is now a 
\series bold
surface integral equation
\series default
 (SIE) for 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

: once we know 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\vec{n}}\cdot\nabla u$
\end_inset

 on the surface, we can get 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 everywhere! Physically, this can be interpreted as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

scattering
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the solution off the 
\emph on
interface
\emph default
 between 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}$
\end_inset

, as represented by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

source
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 terms at every 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}'\in dV$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, 
\series bold
this isn't quite right
\series default
.
 The problem is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla u\cdot\hat{\vec{n}}$
\end_inset

 isn't actually continuous across the interface in general, and so evaluating
 it on the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $dV$
\end_inset

 is not well-defined.
 We can see this by looking at the original equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot(c\nabla n)=f$
\end_inset

: unless 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 happens to have delta functions right on the 
\begin_inset Formula $dV$
\end_inset

 interface, the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $c\nabla u$
\end_inset

 must be continuous across the interface in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\vec{n}}$
\end_inset

 direction.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $c\nabla u\cdot\hat{\vec{n}}$
\end_inset

 is continuous, not 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla u\cdot\hat{\vec{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 So, before we can evaluate a surface integral, we need to rewrite things
 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $c\nabla u\cdot\hat{\vec{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 We can do this, since 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla[\ln c]\cdot\nabla u=\frac{\nabla c}{c}\cdot\nabla u=\frac{\nabla c}{c^{2}}\cdot c\nabla u=\nabla\left(-\frac{1}{c}\right)\cdot c\nabla u\]

\end_inset

in eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VIE"

\end_inset

).
 And 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla(-1/c)$
\end_inset

 is also a delta function multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\vec{n}}$
\end_inset

 and the magnitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{c_{1}}-\frac{1}{c_{2}}$
\end_inset

 of the discontinuity, and hence we obtain a corrected SIE:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
u(\vec{x})=u_{0}(\vec{x})+\left(\frac{1}{c_{1}}-\frac{1}{c_{2}}\right)\oiint_{dV}G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')\left[c(\vec{x}')\nabla'u(\vec{x}')\right]\cdot d\vec{A}',\label{eq:SIE2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is well-defined since the integrand is now a continuous quantity across
 the interface.
 (And even this is not quite in the form that is used in numerics.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like our SIE equations for the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 itself has a boundary, these SIE equations are solved by parameterizing
 the surface unknowns via some discretization, and then choosing the unknowns
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 satisfies appropriate continuity conditions at the interface 
\begin_inset Formula $dV$
\end_inset

.
 The details of this get rather tricky very quickly, but these can yield
 very efficient computational methods because they only involve unknowns
 at interfaces and handle homogeneous regions (even infinite homogeneous
 regions) analytically via 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Born approximation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have written the solution in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $u=u_{0}+\hat{B}u$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the solution due to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 ignoring the inhomogeneity, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 is an integral operator giving the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

scattered
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 portion of the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}u$
\end_inset

 due to the inhomogeneity.
 We can then formally write: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
u & = & u_{0}+\hat{B}u=u_{0}+\hat{B}(u_{0}+\hat{B}u)=u_{0}+\hat{B}u_{0}+\hat{B}^{2}(u_{0}+\hat{B}u_{0}+\hat{B}^{2}u)\\
 & = & \cdots\quad=\left(\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\hat{B}^{k}\right)u_{0},\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which is called a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Born--Dyson
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 series/expansion (sometimes omitting one name or the other).
 Equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\hat{B})u=u_{0}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $u=(1-\hat{B})^{-1}u_{0}$
\end_inset

, and the Taylor series for 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\hat{B})^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}\hat{B}^{k}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What does this represent physically? 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

incident
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 portion of the solution, before scattering off the inhomogeneity.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}u_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the portion of the solution where this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

incident
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 solution has scattered 
\emph on
once
\emph default
 off the inhomogenity, producing a scattered solution 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{B}u_{0}=\int_{\Omega}G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')\nabla'\ln c(\vec{x}')\cdot\nabla'u_{0}(\vec{x}')d^{n}\vec{x}'.\]

\end_inset

But of course, 
\emph on
this
\emph default
 portion of the solution 
\emph on
also
\emph default
 scatters off of the inhomogeneity, producing a portion of the solution
 representing incident solutions that have scattered 
\emph on
twice
\emph default
: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{B}^{2}u_{0}=\int_{\Omega}G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')\nabla'\ln c(\vec{x}')\cdot\nabla'\left[\int_{\Omega}G_{0}(\vec{x}',\vec{x}'')\nabla''\ln c(\vec{x}'')\cdot\nabla''u_{0}(\vec{x}'')d^{n}\vec{x}''\right]d^{n}\vec{x}',\]

\end_inset

i.e.
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}''$
\end_inset

 produces a source term due to 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla''c$
\end_inset

, which 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

travels
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}''$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}'$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}(\vec{x}',\vec{x}'')$
\end_inset

, then produces a source at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}'$
\end_inset

 due to 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla'c$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

travels
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}'$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{G}_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

, and of course this must be integrated over all possible scattering points
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}''$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}^{3}u_{0}$
\end_inset

 represents things scattering three times, and so on.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In quantum mechanics, this kind of series of events is sometimes represented
 graphically by the notation of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Feynman diagrams,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and can be generalized to nonlinear problems and other effectivei inhomogeneiti
es.
 In that context, this process of summing all possible scattering sequences
 is sometimes mysteriously described as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

particle exploring all possible paths between two points,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 but is really just a consequence of particles being described by PDEs (SchrÃ¶din
ger's equation, in single-particle quantum mechanics), rather than ODEs.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, suppose we have a system that is 
\emph on
nearly
\emph default
 homogeneous.
 e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla c$
\end_inset

 is small.
 Then one might expect that the scattered portion 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}u$
\end_inset

 of the solution to be small.
 In this case, we may be able to approximate this series by keeping only
 the first two terms---if scattering 
\emph on
once
\emph default
 has small amplitude, then scattering 
\emph on
twice
\emph default
 should have even smaller amplitude.
 (e.g.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla c$
\end_inset

 is small, this could be thought of as expanding as a power series in 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla c$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}^{k}\sim|\nabla c|^{k}$
\end_inset

.) This is the
\series bold
 Born approximation
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
u(\vec{x})\approx u_{0}(\vec{x})+\hat{B}u_{0},\]

\end_inset

and is an extremely useful way to think about 
\emph on
nearly homogeneous
\emph default
 problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Example: Inhomogeneity in a small volume
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we are solving 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla\cdot(c\nabla u)=f$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 with a point source 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\vec{x})=\delta(\vec{x}-\vec{x}_{0})$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 is piecewise-constant as in figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:piecewise-inhomog"

