\begin_layout Subsection
Dipole sources
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the following problem in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

, requiring as usual that solutions vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
-\nabla^{2}D_{\vec{p}}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')=-\vec{p}\cdot\nabla\delta(\vec{x}-\vec{x}')=+\vec{p}\cdot\nabla'\delta(\vec{x}-\vec{x}').\]

\end_inset

This is like the Green's function equation, except now we have put the 
\emph on
derivative
\emph default
 of a delta function on the right-hand side, with some constant vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}$
\end_inset

 (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dipole moment
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Recall what the derivative of a delta function is: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
[-\vec{p}\cdot\nabla\delta(\vec{x}-\vec{x}')]\{\phi\}=[\delta(\vec{x}-\vec{x}')]\{\vec{p}\cdot\nabla\phi\}=\left.\vec{p}\cdot\nabla\phi\right|_{\vec{x}'}=\lim_{\epsilon\to0}\frac{\phi(\vec{x}'+\epsilon\vec{p})-\phi(\vec{x}'-\epsilon\vec{p})}{2\epsilon},\]

\end_inset

and hence (similar to pset
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

5 of 2010 or pset
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

7 of 2011), 
\begin_inset Formula \[
-\vec{p}\cdot\nabla\delta(\vec{x}-\vec{x}')=\lim_{\epsilon\to0}\frac{\delta(\vec{x}-\vec{x}'-\epsilon\vec{p})-\delta(\vec{x}-\vec{x}'+\epsilon\vec{p})}{2\epsilon}.\]

\end_inset

That is, the derivative of a delta function is a limit of limit of 
\emph on
two
\emph default
 delta functions of 
\emph on
opposite
\emph default
 sign, displaced proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}$
\end_inset

.
 In 8.02, where delta functions are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

point charges,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 this is what you would have called an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

electric dipole.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{D}_{\vec{p}}$
\end_inset

 quite easily, because we know the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla^{2}G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')=\delta(\vec{x}-\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla'$
\end_inset

 derivatives can be interchanged in their order: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
-\vec{p}\cdot\nabla\delta(\vec{x}-\vec{x}')=\vec{p}\cdot\nabla'\left[\delta(\vec{x}-\vec{x}')\right]=\vec{p}\cdot\nabla'\left[-\nabla^{2}G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')\right]=-\nabla^{2}\left[\vec{p}\cdot\nabla'G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')\right],\]

\end_inset

and hence 
\begin_inset Formula \[
D_{\vec{p}}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')=\vec{p}\cdot\nabla'G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')=\vec{p}\cdot\frac{\vec{x}-\vec{x}'}{4\pi|\vec{x}-\vec{x}'|^{3}}.\]

\end_inset

In electrostatics, ths would be the potential of a dipole.
 Note that this falls off as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim1/|\vec{x}-\vec{x}'|^{2}$
\end_inset

, whereas 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}$
\end_inset

 falls off as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim1/|\vec{x}-\vec{x}'|$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

